                type="document" xml:id="d623">
                <head>No. 623<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>The Heads of Government of the United States, France, and the United Kingdom,
                    accompanied by their Foreign Ministers and other advisers, met in Bermuda,
                    December 4–8, 1953, for a series of meetings dealing with problems of mutual
                    concern. For documentation on these meetings, see <ref
                        target="frus1952-54v05p2#pg_1710">volume V, Part 2, pages 1710</ref> ff.</p>
                <p>Following the Bermuda meetings, President <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWER1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> sent messages to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_LANIELJ1">Laniel</persName> and Foreign Minister <persName
                        corresp="#p_BIDAULTG1">Bidault</persName> on December 9. In his message to
                        <persName corresp="#p_BIDAULTG1">Bidault</persName>, President <persName
                        corresp="#p_EISENHOWER1">Eisenhower</persName> expressed his appreciation
                    for <persName corresp="#p_BIDAULTG1">Bidault</persName>’s contributions to the
                    discussions. President <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWER1"
                    >Eisenhower</persName>’s message to President <persName corresp="#p_LANIELJ1"
                        >Laniel</persName> stated his regret that <persName corresp="#p_LANIELJ1"
                        >Laniel</persName>’s illness had prevented him from participating in some of
                    the meetings and wished him a rapid recovery. (Secretary’s Letters, lot 56 D
                    459, “B–C” and “L”)</p>
            </div>
